    <h2>6. Commercial Stove vs Commercial Range — What Is the Difference?</h2>

    <p>This terminology confusion trips up many buyers in India. A <strong>commercial gas stove</strong> (sometimes called a commercial burner) is a standalone unit with one or more burners and no oven. It is typically an open-frame unit with burners on top and an open shelf or gas cylinder storage below. Think of the heavy-duty gas burners you see in dhaba kitchens and catering setups — those are commercial gas stoves.</p>

    <p>A <strong>commercial cooking range</strong>, by contrast, is an enclosed unit that integrates burners on top with an oven (gas or electric) below. The range is a self-contained cooking station: the burners handle stovetop cooking (sauteeing, boiling, frying) while the oven below handles baking, roasting, and gratinating. Ranges are standard equipment in hotel kitchens, fine-dining restaurants, and any operation that needs oven capacity alongside stovetop cooking.</p>

