    <h2>8. Stainless Steel Grades and Build Quality</h2>

    <p>The SS grade of your commercial cooking range affects its durability, corrosion resistance, hygiene compliance, and long-term value. In India, you will encounter three main grades. For a deeper dive into stainless steel equipment considerations, see our <a href="/blog/stainless-steel-kitchen-equipment-india">stainless steel kitchen equipment guide</a>.</p>

    <h3>SS 202 (Budget Grade)</h3>
    <p>SS 202 is the entry-level stainless steel used in budget commercial kitchen equipment. It contains less nickel than SS 304, making it cheaper but also less corrosion-resistant. SS 202 is adequate for equipment that does not come into direct contact with food and is not exposed to harsh cleaning chemicals. It is commonly used in frames, shelves, and the exterior body of budget ranges.</p>
    <p><strong>Lifespan:</strong> 3–5 years in heavy commercial use before visible corrosion, staining, or pitting appears. Acceptable for budget operations where equipment replacement cycles are short.</p>

    <h3>SS 304 (Industry Standard)</h3>
    <p>SS 304 is the industry standard for commercial kitchen equipment worldwide. It contains 18% chromium and 8% nickel, providing excellent corrosion resistance, easy cleaning, and a hygienic surface that meets FSSAI requirements. The vast majority of reputable commercial cooking range brands in India use SS 304 for at least the cooking surface and oven interior.</p>
    <p><strong>Lifespan:</strong> 8–15 years in heavy commercial use with proper maintenance. SS 304 withstands aggressive cleaning agents, high-temperature exposure, and frequent thermal cycling without degradation. This is the grade to insist on for any equipment that touches food or is exposed to heat and moisture.</p>

    <h3>SS 316 (Premium/Marine Grade)</h3>
    <p>SS 316 contains molybdenum in addition to chromium and nickel, giving it superior resistance to chloride corrosion (salt, coastal humidity, acidic foods). It is rarely used in standard commercial cooking ranges in India due to its significantly higher cost (30–50% more than SS 304). SS 316 is specified in coastal restaurants, seafood processing kitchens, and pharmaceutical-grade food production facilities.</p>

    <p><strong>Recommendation for most Indian buyers:</strong> Insist on SS 304 for the cooking surface, burner area, and oven interior. The frame and lower body can be SS 202 or even MS (mild steel) powder-coated to reduce cost without compromising on the surfaces that matter for hygiene, safety, and durability.</p>

    <h2>9. Restaurant Type-Specific Recommendations</h2>

    <p>The right commercial cooking range depends heavily on the type of cuisine and the restaurant format. Here are specific recommendations based on common Indian restaurant types:</p>

    <h3>Indian Restaurant (North Indian / South Indian / Mughlai)</h3>
    <p>Indian restaurant kitchens are defined by high-heat cooking: deep frying puris and samosas, simmering large batches of dal and gravy, tempering (tadka) with smoking-hot oil, and cooking biryani in heavy handis. The cooking range needs to deliver maximum BTU, support heavy vessels, and withstand intense daily use.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Recommended:</strong> 4-burner or 6-burner Indian commercial gas stove (open frame, heavy-duty grates) with 35,000–50,000 BTU per burner.</li>
      <li><strong>Oven needed?</strong> Usually not — Indian restaurants rarely need oven functionality on the range. A separate <a href="/blog/commercial-tandoor-price-india">commercial tandoor</a> handles baking duties.</li>
      <li><strong>Budget:</strong> ₹25,000–₹80,000 for the range; supplement with a separate tandoor and stock pot burner.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Chinese / Indo-Chinese Restaurant</h3>
    <p>Chinese cooking demands extreme heat for wok-based stir-frying. A standard Indian or Western range cannot deliver the 80,000+ BTU needed for proper wok hei. A dedicated Chinese cooking range with waterfall burners is non-negotiable.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Recommended:</strong> 1 or 2 Chinese waterfall burner ranges (80,000–150,000 BTU per burner) plus a standard 2-burner Indian stove for boiling noodles, simmering sauces, and steaming.</li>
      <li><strong>Oven needed?</strong> Rarely. Chinese kitchens use steamers instead.</li>
      <li><strong>Budget:</strong> ₹50,000–₹1,50,000 for the Chinese range setup.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Continental / Multi-Cuisine / Fine Dining</h3>
    <p>Continental cooking requires precision, multiple techniques (sautee, deglaze, reduce, roast), and oven access for gratins, baked dishes, and desserts. A Western-style commercial cooking range with an integrated oven is the standard.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Recommended:</strong> 4-burner or 6-burner Western range with gas oven (or gas burners + electric oven for baking precision). Consider a model with a built-in flat-top griddle section for eggs, pancakes, and seared proteins.</li>
      <li><strong>Oven needed?</strong> Essential. The oven below the range handles a significant portion of continental cooking: roasted meats, baked pastas, gratins, bread rolls.</li>
      <li><strong>Budget:</strong> ₹1,00,000–₹3,50,000 for a quality Western range with oven.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Cloud Kitchen</h3>
    <p>Cloud kitchens prioritise space efficiency and flexibility. Multiple brands/menus may share the same cooking line. The cooking range needs to be compact, versatile, and capable of handling varied cuisines. For full cloud kitchen planning, see our <a href="/blog/cloud-kitchen-equipment">cloud kitchen equipment guide</a>.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Recommended:</strong> Modular approach — a 2-burner or 4-burner Indian stove combined with a single Chinese waterfall burner and a commercial induction cooktop for precision tasks. Avoid large 6-burner ranges unless throughput justifies the space.</li>
      <li><strong>Budget:</strong> ₹40,000–₹1,00,000 for a complete modular cooking range setup.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>10. LPG vs PNG Gas Connections for Commercial Ranges</h2>

    <p>Every commercial cooking range in India runs on either LPG (cylinder-based) or PNG (piped natural gas). The choice affects your operational cost, safety requirements, and equipment specification.</p>

    <h3>LPG (Liquefied Petroleum Gas)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Availability:</strong> Nationwide. Available everywhere in India, from metros to remote towns.</li>
      <li><strong>Supply:</strong> Commercial LPG cylinders (19 kg, also called 47.5 kg in larger formats) delivered by authorised distributors.</li>
      <li><strong>Cost (March 2026):</strong> ₹900–₹1,100 per 19 kg cylinder; ₹2,400–₹2,800 per 47.5 kg cylinder. Costs fluctuate with international crude oil prices.</li>
      <li><strong>Calorific value:</strong> Higher than PNG — LPG delivers approximately 93.2 MJ/m3 vs PNG's 38.7 MJ/m3. This means LPG burners produce more heat per unit volume of gas, requiring smaller orifice sizes.</li>
      <li><strong>Storage requirements:</strong> Cylinders must be stored in a ventilated area away from ignition sources. Fire NOC requirements mandate specific storage distances and quantities. Check local fire department regulations.</li>
      <li><strong>Pressure regulation:</strong> LPG is supplied at higher pressure and requires a pressure regulator on each cylinder or manifold system.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>PNG (Piped Natural Gas)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Availability:</strong> Limited to major cities — Delhi NCR (IGL), Mumbai (Mahanagar Gas), Ahmedabad (Gujarat Gas), Bengaluru (GAIL), Pune, Lucknow, and expanding to other cities under the CGD network.</li>
      <li><strong>Supply:</strong> Continuous piped supply through a metered connection. No cylinder handling, no delivery scheduling.</li>
      <li><strong>Cost:</strong> Typically 20–30% cheaper than LPG per unit of energy delivered. Commercial PNG rates vary by city and slab but generally range ₹35–₹55 per SCM (standard cubic metre) as of March 2026.</li>
      <li><strong>Convenience:</strong> No cylinder changeover during peak service (a major operational advantage). No storage space needed for cylinders.</li>
      <li><strong>Equipment compatibility:</strong> PNG and LPG use different gas pressures and orifice sizes. You cannot directly connect an LPG range to a PNG line (or vice versa) without changing the burner orifices. Most brands offer models in both LPG and PNG variants, or provide conversion kits. Always specify your gas type at the time of purchase.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> If PNG is available in your area, switch to it. The cost savings (20–30% lower fuel bills), operational convenience (no cylinder logistics), and safety improvements (no stored cylinders) make it the superior choice for any established restaurant. If PNG is not available, use LPG with a manifold system for automatic cylinder switchover during service. Refer to our <a href="/blog/fssai-license-cost-registration-india">FSSAI licence and registration guide</a> for compliance details related to gas installations.</p>

    <h2>11. Installation &amp; Ventilation Requirements</h2>

    <p>Proper installation of a commercial cooking range is critical for safety, efficiency, and regulatory compliance. Here are the key requirements:</p>

    <h3>Clearances</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Wall clearance:</strong> Minimum 150 mm (6 inches) from any combustible wall or surface. For non-combustible walls (tile, SS backsplash), 50 mm is acceptable.</li>
      <li><strong>Overhead clearance:</strong> Minimum 750 mm between the cooking surface and the bottom of the exhaust hood. For high-BTU equipment (Chinese waterfall burners), 900 mm is recommended to prevent hood filter damage from direct flame exposure.</li>
      <li><strong>Adjacent equipment:</strong> Leave 50–100 mm gaps between ranges and adjacent equipment for cleaning access and heat dissipation.</li>
      <li><strong>Floor:</strong> The range must sit on a level, non-combustible floor (tile, concrete, or SS floor plate). Adjustable feet are standard on most commercial ranges — use them to level the unit precisely.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Ventilation</h3>
    <p>Every commercial cooking range must operate under a properly sized exhaust hood. The exhaust hood captures heat, grease vapour, smoke, and combustion gases from the cooking process. Without adequate ventilation, your kitchen becomes an unsafe, uncomfortable, and non-compliant environment. For a comprehensive guide on hood sizing and selection, see our <a href="/blog/commercial-exhaust-hood">commercial exhaust hood guide</a>.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hood overhang:</strong> The exhaust hood must extend at least 150 mm beyond the cooking range on all open sides.</li>
      <li><strong>Airflow (CFM):</strong> Calculate the required exhaust airflow based on hood type and cooking equipment. For a wall-mounted hood over a standard cooking range, the formula is: Length (ft) x Width (ft) x 100 CFM = Required airflow. For high-heat equipment (Chinese burners, charcoal grills), multiply by 150–200 CFM.</li>
      <li><strong>Make-up air:</strong> For every cubic foot of air exhausted, your kitchen needs an equal volume of make-up air supplied. Without make-up air, the kitchen develops negative pressure, pulling unconditioned air through doors and service openings — increasing cooling costs and creating uncomfortable drafts.</li>
      <li><strong>Fire suppression:</strong> Kitchens with open-flame equipment (which includes all gas cooking ranges) should have a fire suppression system integrated with the exhaust hood, per National Building Code 2016 guidelines. At minimum, keep Class K fire extinguishers within 10 feet of the cooking range.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Gas Line Installation</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Qualified installer:</strong> Gas line installation must be done by a licensed gas fitter. DIY gas connections are illegal and dangerous.</li>
      <li><strong>Shut-off valve:</strong> A manual gas shut-off valve must be accessible within 1 metre of the range, allowing quick gas isolation in an emergency.</li>
      <li><strong>Leak testing:</strong> All gas connections must be soap-tested for leaks after installation and periodically thereafter (monthly is recommended for commercial kitchens).</li>
      <li><strong>Gas pipe material:</strong> Copper or approved flexible gas connectors. GI (galvanised iron) piping is standard for fixed PNG connections.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>12. Maintenance Guide for Commercial Cooking Ranges</h2>

    <p>A well-maintained commercial cooking range lasts 10–15 years. A neglected one breaks down in 3–4 years and wastes gas throughout its shortened life. Here is a practical maintenance schedule:</p>

    <h3>Daily Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Wipe down all surfaces with a damp cloth and mild degreaser after each service.</li>
      <li>Remove burner grates and clean off food debris, spilled liquids, and grease.</li>
      <li>Check that all burner flames are blue and even. Yellow or irregular flames indicate clogged burner ports or incorrect air-fuel mixture.</li>
      <li>Clean the oven interior (if applicable) — remove any spills or splatters while still warm (they are harder to remove once cooled).</li>
      <li>Empty and clean the drip tray under the burners.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Weekly Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Deep clean burner grates in hot soapy water. Use a wire brush to remove carbonised deposits.</li>
      <li>Remove burner caps and clean the burner ports with a thin wire or needle — clogged ports reduce efficiency and cause uneven flames.</li>
      <li>Clean the oven interior thoroughly with an oven-specific degreaser (not a general-purpose cleaner, which can damage oven seals and interior coatings).</li>
      <li>Inspect gas hoses and connections for wear, cracking, or looseness. Replace any suspect components immediately.</li>
      <li>Check and clean the pilot lights (if fitted) — dirty pilots cause ignition failures and gas wastage.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Monthly Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Perform a soap-solution leak test on all gas connections — apply soapy water to joints and watch for bubbles.</li>
      <li>Calibrate oven temperature using an independent oven thermometer. Oven thermostats drift over time; recalibrate or replace if the reading deviates by more than 10°C from the set temperature.</li>
      <li>Inspect flame failure devices (FFDs) by deliberately blowing out a burner and confirming that the gas supply cuts off within 30 seconds.</li>
      <li>Lubricate gas valve stems (if applicable) with food-grade lubricant to prevent stiffness.</li>
      <li>Clean the area behind and below the range — grease and debris accumulate in these hidden zones and create fire hazards.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Annual Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Full service by a qualified technician: burner inspection, orifice cleaning, thermocouple replacement if needed, gas pressure testing, and oven calibration.</li>
      <li>Replace gas hoses — even if they appear undamaged, flexible gas hoses should be replaced annually as a precaution.</li>
      <li>Inspect and replace oven door seals if they show signs of hardening, cracking, or gaps (poor seals waste energy and cause uneven baking).</li>
      <li>Review the exhaust hood and grease filters above the range — a poorly maintained hood affects the range's performance and fire safety.</li>
    </ul>

